{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:39:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:39:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18790"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18790"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.09,0.08,0.25,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78667"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64010"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44318"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78667"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with a three-day history of fever, productive cough, and shortness of breath. She has stage 5 chronic kidney disease due to IgA nephropathy and is being worked up for dialysis. Her medications include calcium carbonate, calcitriol, sodium bicarbonate, irbesartan, and furosemide. Her condition improves with antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn day of planned discharge, investigations are performed which reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 67 g/L (115-165) \u003Cbr /\u003EMean cell volume: 85 fL (80-96)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 11.2 x 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count: 350 x 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn admission, haemoglobin was 77 g/L (115-165).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is LEAST likely to be helpful in the management of her anaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measurement of serum vitamin B12","Measurement of serum ferritin","Assessment of menstrual blood loss","Per rectal examination","Initiation of erythropoiesis-stimulating agent"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe anaemia in the context of stage 5 chronic kidney disease (CKD). The normocytic anaemia is most likely multifactorial, primarily due to reduced erythropoietin production by the failing kidneys and functional iron deficiency. As with all patients, overt bleeding needs to be identified and addressed. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasurement of serum vitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E is least likely to be helpful in this scenario. While B12 deficiency can cause anaemia, it typically presents with macrocytosis and is not a common contributing factor to anaemia in CKD. The normal mean cell volume in this case makes B12 deficiency less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssessment of menstrual blood loss\u003C/strong\u003E is important in any pre-menopausal woman with anaemia. A history about gastrointestinal bleeding +/- a \u003Cstrong\u003Eper rectal examination \u003C/strong\u003Eis important to evaluate GI bleeding, as opposed to assuming the anaemia is only CKD-related. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasurement of serum ferritin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EInitiation of erythropoiesis-stimulating agent\u003C/strong\u003E are both beneficial. Ideally if iron deficiency is identified, this should be addressed before commencing an erythropoiesis-stimulating agent, given the process of erythropoiesis utilises iron. Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents are less effective in states of iron deficiency. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anaemia in chronic kidney disease is often related to erythropoietin deficiency. However, it is important not to overlook overt causes of bleeding."],"references":["Badireddy M, Baradhi KM. Chronic Anemia. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534803/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64010"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64010"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T22:20:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T22:20:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78667"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"po